Chapter 1
Cohren
4:30, Itania time. Cohren hated waking up that early. Especially since it was his responsibility to wake up all the other members of his company. Silently exiting his bed, he put on his combat uniform, his tactical vest, and gathered his belongings from his locker, paying special attention to a small box. He placed his rifle on his shoulder and hung his helmet on a small hook attached to his belt. The helmet was fully equipped: respirator, goggles, everything necessary. After checking his ammo pockets, he calmly left the barracks, the sound of crushed mud and ice echoing under his boots.
He pulled out a lighter from his vest pocket and a cigarette from the other. Lighting it, he took a small puff before opening the door slowly. The previous week, he had to be creative to wake up the men and women under his command. He stopped using the pre-set alarm clock, half the time it didn't work, because everything that came out of the speakers was a faint whistle.
"Waking them up?" Cohren turned around to see Second Lieutenant Nemic arriving on foot.
"Ouep", responded Cohren.
"What have you planned to use this time?"
Before he could respond, the door opened and Harris, Craith, and other soldiers hurried out, already dressed and equipped.
"Good morning," said Craith.
"What woke you up?", asked Cohren.
"Eh bien, primo, we didn't want to see what you had planned to wake us up today. Secundo, the first shock troops up are the first to breakfast." One of them, Ravik, replied: "And you know how bad it can be".
"You're right, Specialist," said Cohren. He stretched out his hand and flipped a switch. A loud, screaming alarm resounded inside the barracks, and he heard commotion and agitation inside.
"Good Lord, Valturi," Nemic shouted. "We could have thought they would have learned to wake up at the same time as you by now."
"Well, my training camp buddies here made it," Cohren turned to Harris, Craith, and Ravik. "But, once again, their squad and platoon commanders know how to wake up before their units do."
A few seconds later, the rest of the company came out in mass. Everyone had what they needed, from personal belongings to necessary equipment. Some of the new recruits seemed disoriented, others more annoyed.
"Good morning, everyone," Cohren said with a cheerful voice.
"Spare our respect, chief, why do you insist on waking us up this way?", asked one of the shock troop members, a corporal.
"Because standard wake-ups are terrible. And because Daybreak doesn't sleep in," Cohren replied.
"Make sure you have all your personal belongings," he continued. As the first lieutenant and assistant to the commander, it was his responsibility to supervise and assist the company with the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. "We're not coming back. Sergeants and second lieutenants, I give you and your units fifty minutes to perform the final checks and pick up rations for the day."
The members of Company Exodus dispersed. They were part of the Second Shock Troop Division, Second Army. Initially, they were separated into two distinct companies, Cohort and Dragger, before being reunited. It was a split company, and Cohren didn't know what to think of his promotion to first lieutenant, mainly the reasons that motivated him.
Cohren and Second Lieutenant Nemic, the first platoon leader, walked together under the light of numerous illuminations of the advanced operational base, powered by generators. Most of them were painted red to hide them from enemy bombers. Daybreak had resorted to Wild Weasel assaults, both in the air and on the ground, to combat them.
"New day, new mission for the pioneers of hell," Nemic started with a dry laugh. "Where are they sending us?"
"An advanced operational base outside of Ianlos. We've been sent to support the ground assault," Cohren replied, pulling on his cigarette. Part of him blamed Craith for introducing him to smoking, but a year of combat had changed a man, and he remained silent.
"Shit. The situation is deteriorating on the front," Nemic muttered. "All the news coming from that place is 'Contribute to the war effort. Send aid to the Kurgan front.' Why not send aid to the Howland front?"
"Amen, brother," Cohren said, flicking his cigarette butt into the mud. "Anyway, we're leaving with the first armored platoon, so we won't have to walk. Captain Shaw should be there."
"Shaw got us a transport?", Nemic asked, a bit surprised.
"Ouep. Honestly, he's not as bad as I thought. I mean, he's not exceptional, but he's not unbearable."
Cohren raised his thumb and index finger to his throat mic while adjusting his backpack. "To all units of Company Exodus, assemble at the west vehicle park when you're done. We're leaving with the first armored platoon at 5:00."
Every few seconds, he received responses from the squadron leaders. Harris, Craith, and Ravik were all junior non-commissioned officers when they arrived here. All four had been close friends since their initial training on Earth. It seemed like a long time ago, even though it couldn't have been more than two years. They were then squadron leaders. But Craith now commanded the second platoon for a week, after the demobilization of the previous commander, injured by a Daybreak sniper.
As they walked towards the vehicle park, Cohren and Nemic saw a group of around eight main battle tanks Kronos and four Strykers. Their crew was busy, making sure their war machines were ready for departure. Cohren quickly spotted Captain Boradin Shaw, who was talking to the commander of the armored platoon. As they approached, Shaw turned and walked towards them, his usually cold face reflecting no emotion.
"Lieutenant Nemic... Lieutenant Valturi...". He said that Cohren was slower, looking at Cohren's pistol case before looking at them again. "I suppose the company is ready."
